JO  - Journal of Small Business and Enterprise Development
PY  - 2025
AB  - Over the past decades, thanks to a continuous process of digitalization, the financial industry has witnessed the advent and growth of new providers alongside traditional intermediaries, experiencing radical changes across all areas of service provision (e.g. Alalwan et al., 2024; Bertoni et al., 2022; Gomber et al., 2017). The very essence of finance and banking—namely, lending and capital provision—has been particularly and deeply affected by digital transformation (e.g. Chen et al., 2019; Cong and He, 2019; Thakor, 2020; Battisti et al., 2022), as the search for funding by start-ups, new entrepreneurial initiatives, and well-established micro, small and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs) (e.g. Beltrame et al., 2023; Fadil and St-Pierre, 2021). The COVID-19 pandemic further accelerated digitalization processes (Boot et al., 2021) and challenged traditional sources of capital that supported entrepreneurs (e.g. Howell et al., 2020; Rao et al., 2024).However, it remains unclear whether this digital revolution represents a threat or an opportunity for enterprises seeking funding. On the one hand, it introduces new types of financial sources and reduces the time needed to secure financing; on the other hand, the proliferation of innovative funding sources for new ventures has substantially increased the complexity of the start-up financing ecosystem (Bertoni et al., 2022). Therefore, the effect of digitalization on entrepreneurial finance—and more broadly, on the sources of funding for small and medium-sized enterprises—deserves further investigation.This Special Issue sought contributions that helped better understand the new global landscape of the entrepreneurial finance ecosystem by exploring in depth the role played by digitalization, artificial intelligence and machine learning. The aim was to provide insights, pathways, and tools to financial and management scholars, as well as to CEOs, CFOs, owners of MSMEs, entrepreneurs, start-up leaders and new financial intermediaries. We accepted papers from diverse epistemological, theoretical and methodological backgrounds for this Special Issue.The following section presents a synopsis of the contributions included in this Special Issue.This Special Issue comprises ten papers from different fields, each offering novel, informative content and implications for scholars and practitioners around the world.In particular, our Special Issue commences by setting a broad analytical foundation for digital finance in the small business context. Modina et al. (2025) provide this essential overview in their paper “Digital finance for SMEs and startups: a bibliometric analysis and future research direction”. Their comprehensive bibliometric review meticulously maps the academic landscape of digital finance concerning SMEs and startups, identifying key trends, influential authors and thematic clusters. This work not only offers a foundational understanding but also critically pinpoints existing research gaps, charting promising future directions for studies into the practical implementation and tangible impact of digital financial tools on entrepreneurial growth and sustainability.Building on this pervasive influence of digitalization, Rehman et al. (2025) delve into the specific nexus between digital entrepreneurship and environmental performance (EP) within manufacturing SMEs, as explored in “Digital entrepreneurship! Nexus among industry 4.0 enablers, environmental dynamism and SMEs environmental performance: a mediated-moderated perspectives”. Their mediated-moderated model reveals how digital technologies and digital organizational culture influence EP, with innovation capacity as a crucial mediator, and perceived environmental volatility alongside green strategic intent as significant moderators. This study offers valuable insights into how SMEs can strategically harness digital advancements for both operational efficiency and environmental sustainability.Transitioning from the general impact of digitalization, several papers in this issue focus on innovative financing mechanisms and their implications for micro and small businesses. Singh et al. (2025a) address the perennial concern of access to finance for Indian MSMEs in their paper “Access to finance and its impact on operational efficiency of MSMEs: mediating role of entrepreneurial personality and self-efficacy”. Their research highlights how access to finance impacts operational efficiency, crucially identifying the mediating role of entrepreneurial self-efficacy (ESE) and entrepreneurial personality, underscoring the pivotal role of individual psychological attributes. Expanding on alternative financing, Singh et al. (2025b) assess entrepreneurial business performance (EBP) through the dynamic capability and technology–organization–environment (TOE) frameworks, specifically examining the moderating role of crowdfunding support, in “Assessing the entrepreneurial business performance from a dynamic capability and TOE framework: moderating role of crowdfunding support”. Their model demonstrates how ventures can bolster performance by effectively leveraging dynamic capabilities within technological and organizational contexts, often amplified by crowdfunding’s flexibility. Further exploring novel financial instruments, Bužinskė et al. (2025) address a critical gap in green finance by modeling the application of green mini-bonds for environmentally beneficial projects, with a practical case study on municipal waste reduction, in “Modelling financing mechanisms using mini bonds for green and zero-waste projects”. Their analysis provides a robust framework for policymakers and organizations seeking innovative financial instruments to support sustainable development.However, the rapid ascent of new financial technologies is not without its complexities and potential pitfalls. This issue also critically examines the “dark side” of these innovations. Sestino et al. (2025) investigate this aspect in their paper “The ‘dark side’ and negative consequences of cryptocurrencies usage for unethical purposes as barriers to invest in Middle East and African (MEA) countries”. Their explorative research highlights how the use of cryptocurrencies for illicit activities such as money laundering and terrorism financing poses significant barriers to legitimate investment in MEA countries, emphasizing the urgent need for robust regulatory frameworks. Complementing this, the evolving landscape of public market access for digital firms is explored by Anconetani et al. (2025) in “Are SPACs a good investment deal for investors? A performance comparison between SPACS vs IPOs”. Their comparative study rigorously analyzes the post-business combination performance of special purpose acquisition companies (SPACs) against traditional initial public offerings (IPOs) within the digital sector. Their findings indicate that SPACs generally underperform matched IPOs in both operating and stock market metrics, offering crucial insights for investors and entrepreneurs weighing this rapid public market route against its inherent risks. The resilience of emerging financial instruments during global shocks is further addressed by Ballis et al. (2025) in “The impact of COVID-19 first wave on cryptocurrencies and G7 stock markets”. Their paper investigates the differential impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic’s initial wave on cryptocurrency markets versus traditional G7 stock markets, utilizing a difference-in-differences methodology, shedding light on the evolving role of cryptocurrencies during periods of high uncertainty.Finally, we delve deeper into the technological underpinnings of digital finance and the human element crucial for its success within entrepreneurial ventures. Robusti et al. (2025) provide a systematic literature review on the transformative potential of blockchain technology and smart contracts in digital entrepreneurial finance and venture funding, in their paper “Blockchain and smart contracts: transforming digital entrepreneurial finance and venture funding”. Their analysis highlights how these technologies enhance transparency, security, and efficiency, revealing their capacity to significantly disrupt traditional funding models through automated contract execution and reduced administrative overheads, fostering a more decentralized and efficient financial ecosystem for startups. Concluding this insightful issue, Del Sarto et al. (2025) address a notable research gap by investigating the critical impact of team diversity on the success of initial coin offerings (ICOs) in their paper “The importance of team diversity in initial coin offerings (ICO) success”. By compiling a comprehensive database and employing econometric modeling, their study demonstrates that diverse teams – those encompassing a wider array of skills, experiences, and perspectives – are positively correlated with ICO success. This offers invaluable strategic insights for both entrepreneurs launching projects and investors navigating the burgeoning and increasingly competitive cryptocurrency funding landscape.In sum, the papers presented in this Special Issue collectively offer a rich tapestry of research, highlighting the multifaceted nature of digital entrepreneurial finance. The accepted papers provide a foundational understanding of current trends, expose inherent challenges and propose innovative solutions, thereby contributing significantly to both academic discourse and practical application in this vital field. The guest editors of this Special Issue hope that this collection will stimulate further research and guide practitioners in navigating the complexities and seizing the opportunities that lie at the intersection of digital innovation, finance and sustainability.Lastly, the guest editors would like to express their deep gratitude to the Editor-in-Chief of the Journal, Prof. Patrick J. Murphy, for his unwavering support and for granting us the outstanding opportunity to lead this Special Issue; his guidance and trust have been instrumental throughout the entire editorial process. We also sincerely thank the anonymous reviewers for their valuable time and constructive feedback, as well as all the authors who submitted their contributions and helped make this Special Issue possible.
