AU  - S Adapa
AU  - Mary-Louise Conway
AU  - Subba Reddy Yarram
TI  - Entrepreneurial Finance for Start-ups and Scale-ups: Empirical Evidence from Founders Located in Regional Australia
JO  - RUNE (Research UNE)
PY  - 2025
AB  - Financial capital is important to a start-up/scale-up’s existence and obtaining it externally via entrepreneurial finance (including debt, grants, and equity) may enable venture success. Successful start-ups/scale-ups have been demonstrated to generate positive economic and cultural flow-on effects for local communities that are particularly valuable in regional contexts. Obtaining financial capital via entrepreneurial finance (EF) is challenging, and the segmented literature reports many complex and interrelated contributing factors. A focus on the micro level (individual founder) can provide insights for application in practice by founders and can address the gaps in the literature, including those related to segmentation by source and type of EF, venture-stage, and the minimal attention on regional locations. The objective of this study was to explore the lived experiences of 20 founders located in regional Australia and describe their current situation to provide insights into their reported EF challenges. The founders’ views, experiences, actions, and characteristics were identified via semi-structured interviews and questionnaires. The conceptually driven interpretivist approach utilised concepts from signaling theory and image theory to provide an overarching terminology regardless of the type/source of EF that founders pursued. Conceptual depth was added by referring to human, psychological, cognitive, and social capital as well as personality traits. Inductive concepts that arose during the thematic and content analysis were coded. The iterative nature of this exploratory research resulted in multiple literature reviews, conceptual frameworks, and information collected to inform the analysis. The findings showed that participants were using a learn-as-you-go approach (learn-from-doing and learn-while-doing) in a mostly unstructured manner. A learn-as-you-go approach is wellsuited to the entrepreneurial context; however, this approach would be most effective when combined with a system/structure and self-agentic/reflective tools to expedite optimal and timely outcomes. In undertaking an ongoing process of becoming prepared, many EF challenges stemmed from knowledge, skills, strategies, and contacts being at levels other than what was best needed for the task at hand. Challenges were compounded by the inadequate EF resources/contacts available in the regional location and by broader issues at the meso and macro levels. Using founder characteristics as the lens, the findings imply that the faster the founder can accumulate, interpret, and integrate the relevant actionable learnings and skills and couple these with conducive states, the more efficiently and effectively they can act to navigate and adapt their dynamic journey to successful EF outcomes. The thesis concludes that content-based EF education for founders (e.g., knowledge of all aspects of the EF process) is necessary but not sufficient for successful EF outcomes, and measures to address EF challenges need to be both educational and also transformative/catalytic in nature to empower and leverage the self-agency of the individual founder and support their agentic endeavours in the contextually dynamic environment of entrepreneurship and EF. The impacts of timing and chance were concluded to play a role in EF outcomes irrespective of plans or preparations. The research contributes to the field in several ways: it describes the EF process without segmentation by type/source of EF, it uses a descriptive, exploratory approach that complements the many quantitative hypothesis-bound EF studies, it focuses on regionally located participants, it provides an understanding of current lived experiences that can inform those who help founders (e.g., incubators, accelerators, advisors, and policy makers), and it suggests avenues of change for implementation in practice and for future research to explore.
