TI  - From Rumors to Reality: Exploring Machine Learning Approaches for Fake News Detection
PY  - 2025
AB  - Before the Internet was even a known thing, there was malicious deception and fake news. The widespread acceptance of fake news on social media can be attributed to the proliferation of misleading articles and their ability to captivate readers. Both social media platforms and news publishers often share such misleading content to expand their audience and gain market traction. Clickbait increases the spirit of inquiry among people. It's a matter of notable concern to look upon it as it damages the national and social inbuilt powerhouse. The dissemination of false news within the modern digital environment affects more than just one particular demographic. In social media, material that is both credible and implausible is mixed together, confusing what is real. In other words, the truth won't likely be classified. There has previously been much investigation before it was discovered. This paper conducts a comprehensive examination of the existing literature pertaining to the identification of fake news. It also delves into the exploration of prominent conventional machine learning models with the aim of constructing a classification algorithm. This algorithm is designed to discern between authentic and counterfeit news by utilizing various tools including Python, PorterStemmer, Fuzzy-logic, and Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques for textual analysis. According to the experimental findings, the Passive Aggressive Classifier has a 96% accuracy rate.
