AU  - Hao Zhang
TI  - Three Essays on Private Equity and Venture Capital
JO  - Open MIND
PY  - 2026
AB  - This thesis consists of three studies on private equity (PE) and venture capital (VC). It explores how these investment institutions create value, and how their strategic behavior affects investor perceptions, the allocation of financial and human capital, and long-term economic dynamism. In the first study, I examine whether private equity funds use add-on acquisitions in their portfolio firms to create an illusion of earnings growth. Focusing on firms that go public through an IPO, I find that those with a high volume of add-on transactions underperform their peers by approximately 7% in the post-IPO period, particularly when IPO prospectuses fail to clearly disclose the sources of earnings growth. These firms not only generate more negative abnormal returns but also attract overly optimistic earnings forecasts from professional analysts, consistent with misperceptions about the sustainability of growth. Furthermore, PE sponsors tend to exit these add-on-intensive firms significantly earlier after listing, suggesting a strategic effort to capitalize on temporarily inflated valuations. Collectively, the findings suggest that PE funds may use add-on acquisitions to construct a misleading narrative of operational performance, leading public investors to overvalue these firms. The effects are especially pronounced during periods of economic downturn, when organic growth is harder to achieve. These results underscore the importance of mandating clear, pro forma disclosure of the sources of pre-IPO earnings growth in IPO filings. The second study investigates whether the extreme successes often observed in venture capital fund returns reflect genuine investment skill or are largely attributable to luck. While VC investment returns are typically highly skewed, I document substantial variation across funds in the skewness of their within-fund return distributions. A theoretical model developed in this paper shows that when portfolio size is limited, a single outlier can significantly distort average returns, making it difficult to distinguish skill from luck. Using proprietary portfolio company-level return data, I provide empirical evidence consistent with the model’s predictions. Funds with highly skewed return distributions are less likely to sustain strong performance in their successor funds compared to those with more broadly distributed above-average returns. Although some firms may deliberately pursue high-skewness strategies, such outcomes are not reliably replicated. Nonetheless, these funds are more likely to raise follow-on capital, suggesting that limited partners may place disproportionate weight on standout successes. These findings underscore the importance of looking beyond headline IRRs and considering the structure of returns when evaluating GP skill. The third study investigates how corporate venture capital (CVC) investors extract strategic value from failed start-up investments. The analysis shows that, compared with successful exits, failed CVC-backed start-ups are more likely to expose parent firms to novel technological domains, offering strategic benefits despite the absence of financial returns. CVCs appear to invest in these ventures not only for their exploratory potential but also to gain insights into competing technologies and enhance their own competitive positioning. Following failure, CVC parent firms are more likely to cite and acquire patents from these start-ups and to hire inventors with expertise in unfamiliar technological areas, thereby integrating both codified and tacit knowledge into their innovation pipelines. This study highlights the dual role of CVCs in knowledge acquisition and in facilitating the reallocation of innovation resources and talent following venture failure. Collectively, these chapters contribute to a deeper understanding of how private capital markets operate under uncertainty and asymmetry. They emphasize the risks of overinterpreting success signals, the informational role of extreme success, and the strategic behavior of investors in allocating resources.
