AB  - This dissertation focuses on corporate venture capital (CVC) investments as an essential element for organizations to innovate and gain competitive advantages. This is of relevance as organizations are increasingly confronted with persistent and radical changes in their environment (e.g., rapid and complex technological change). However, they can only build up the necessary knowledge to create innovations to survive in this dynamic environment through internal R&D in a limited way. As a result, organizations are dependent on external sources of knowledge, which they can exploit through CVC investments. The purpose of this dissertation is to address under-researched segments in the existing CVC literature to improve the understanding of CVC investments through studies on impacts, implications, and interrelations. To do so, one empirical paper examines the impacts on the formation of a CVC capability that in turn affects the outcome of a CVC investment. A second empirical paper examines the implications of CVC investments in competition and thus the longevity of investment-related benefits. The last paper, a literature review, deals with the interrelations between CVC investments and other external activities (e.g., alliances and acquisitions) by considering CVC investments as a nexus to these external activities. Within this study, the current state of divergent literature is summarized and research gaps as well as future research opportunities are identified. The dissertation starts with a general introduction to CVC with the intention of presenting the relevance, special characteristics, and commonalities of the aforementioned papers. This is followed by the individual papers, starting with the empirical study on CVC capability, continuing with the empirical study on the implications in competition and concluding with the literature review.
