TI  - Law enforcement quality and venture capital Efficiency: Evidence from China
JO  - International Review of Economics & Finance
PY  - 2025
AB  - : This study examines how regional variations in law enforcement quality influence venture capital (VC) efficiency across Chinese provinces, despite the existence of a unified national legal system. Drawing on a comprehensive dataset comprising 20,982 VC investment rounds from 2000 to 2018, we find that regions with stronger law enforcement are significantly more likely to experience successful VC exits. These findings remain robust after addressing potential endogeneity issues and conducting extensive sensitivity analyses. Further investigation identifies three key mechanisms through which improved law enforcement quality enhances VC performance: fostering innovation efficiency, alleviating financing constraints, and reinforcing social trust between investors and investees. Additionally, we observe that this positive relationship is attenuated by syndicated investments, geopolitical risks, dialectal disparities between VCs and portfolio firms, and greater geographical distance. Conversely, the presence of international venture capital strengthens the beneficial impact of law enforcement quality. Overall, our results underscore the pivotal role of regional law enforcement in facilitating the growth of emerging industries via venture capital.
