AB  - This paper offers a theorization of contrarianism in Silicon Valley, presenting it as a strategic rationality underpinned by institutional infrastructure. Rather than treating contrarianism as principled dissent, I conceptualize it as a form of mimetic speculation embedded in the political economy of venture capital. Drawing on political theory, political economy, and accounts of mimetic desire, I develop the concept of negative mimesis to provide an explanation of how dissent is curated, aestheticized, and ultimately instrumentalized within contemporary innovation regimes. I argue that in environments characterized by uncertainty, substantive demonstration matters less than the performance of rupture, the anticipation of convergence, and the promise of value capture. The argument unfolds in three parts. First, I examine the political theory of dissent, drawing on Thiel’s opposition of freedom and democracy to engage with Mill, Foucault, and Rancière. I argue that contrarianism appropriates the style of dissensus while discursively displacing its political substance. Second, I turn to political economy, theorizing contrarianism as a form of mimetic arbitrage. I show how contrarianism is structured around speculative bets on future consensus rather than the disruption of concentrated power. Third, I explore the institutional conditions that enable this strategy, focusing on how venture capital distributes risk through portfolio structures, cultivating reputational resilience alongside narrative infrastructures that render speculation credible. Taken together, each part builds a case of how contrarianism operates as a performative rationality that manufactures, rather than opposes, consensus and conformity in contemporary capitalist society.
