TI  - The “Venture Capital State”
PY  - 2025
AB  - Abstract China’s economic rise, state-led technological progress, and authoritarian political system have spurred fears that it could destabilize the global order. Systemic differences between China and the United States and its allies are permanent, but China’s economic outperformance is not. China’s development strategy under Xi Jinping relies heavily on investment in technology-intensive manufacturing while doing little to improve overall efficiency. On current policies, average annual gross domestic product growth should fall to around 3%, and China will probably fail to overtake the United States as the world’s largest economy. But it will keep making rapid progress in key technologies, and this progress will be seen as a threat by the United States and its allies. Because most countries have a strong interest in deep economic ties with both powers, the United States and China will not form exclusive blocs as in the Cold War but will compete in overlapping networks of influence.
