TI  - The Interactive Relationship Between Venture Debt and Governmental Venture Capital
JO  - Advances in Economics Management and Political Sciences
PY  - 2026
AB  - Against the backdrop of the global wave of technological innovation, the financing difficulties of tech start-ups have become increasingly prominent. As core tools of tech finance, the collaborative operation of governmental venture capital (GVC) and venture debt (VD) is crucial to alleviating the financing predicament of enterprises. Aiming at the insufficient discussion on the synergy and substitution relationship between the two financing tools in existing research, this paper sorts out the core domestic and foreign literature through the literature review method. It analyzes the certification and resource support functions of GVC, as well as the financing logic and decision-making basis of VD, and clarifies their action paths under different scenarios. The research shows that GVC has a dual impact on enterprises' VD financing capacity: policy endorsement and resource integration can increase the probability of obtaining VD, while the capital allocation deviation caused by policy orientation reduces enterprises' solvency and market recognition, thus weakening the availability of VD. In actual operation, the two form functional complementarity, but also have a substitution relationship due to differences in policy intervention and market preferences. Based on the shortcomings of existing research, this paper provides reference ideas for the optimization of the tech finance system, the improvement of enterprises' financing structure and policy formulation.
