TI  - Gender Differences in Access to Entrepreneurial Finance : A Study of Women Entrepreneurs in Uttar Pradesh
JO  - Zenodo (CERN European Organization for Nuclear Research)
PY  - 2026
AB  - Access to finance remains one of the most significant constraints faced by women entrepreneurs in developing economies. This paper examines gender differences in access to formal entrepreneurial finance in Uttar Pradesh (UP), India, with a specific focus on government-led credit and formalization initiatives. Using secondary administrative data from Udyam Registration, Pradhan Mantri Mudra Yojana (PMMY), and the Stand-Up India Scheme, the study analyses trends from FY 2021–22 to FY 2023–24 and benchmarks UP’s performance against other major Indian states. The findings reveal a sharp increase in formalization among women-led MSMEs in UP, extensive outreach of microcredit under PMMY, and comparatively limited participation in higher-ticket financing through Stand-Up India. At the national level, women account for a majority of PMMY loan accounts but receive a smaller share of the total sanctioned amount, indicating a persistent ticket-size gap. The paper concludes with policy recommendations to strengthen the financing pipeline for women entrepreneurs in Uttar Pradesh.
