TY  - JOUR
AU  - Suraj Kumar H M
TI  - Startup Growth vs Security Readiness: Evaluating Vulnerability Disclosure Adoption in India
JO  - Zenodo (CERN European Organization for Nuclear Research)
PY  - 2026
AB  - India hosts one of the world’s largest concentrations of funded technology startups; however, security governance practices, particularly those related to vulnerability disclosure, have not scaled proportionately with organizational growth. This paper examines the adoption of Vulnerability Disclosure Programs (VDPs) and Coordinated Vulnerability Disclosure (CVD) practices within the Indian startup ecosystem, with a specific focus on the fintech, edtech, and healthtech sectors. The study combines secondary research with manual observational analysis of a non-exhaustive sample of ten Indian startups. It evaluates several structured disclosure indicators, including the presence of a security.txt file, designated security contact channels, publicly available VDP policies, hall-of-fame acknowledgements, and safe-harbor language. The findings indicate that formal VDP adoption remains critically low across the observed sample. Although approximately 60% of the organizations provided a security@ email address, these channels generally lacked defined triage processes, response timelines, or legal clarity for security researchers. The paper identifies and categorizes seven structural barriers to VDP adoption and benchmarks India’s disclosure environment against practices commonly observed in the United States and the European Union. In addition, three operational case studies are presented to illustrate recurring interaction patterns between researchers and organizations. To address these gaps, the paper proposes a staged, zero-cost Minimum Viable Vulnerability Disclosure Program (MV-VDP) framework designed for organizations without dedicated security teams or formal security budgets. The study concludes with policy recommendations for regulators, investors, and startup founders, while also acknowledging the empirical limitations associated with an independently conducted observational study.
